The following table provides half-lives and corresponding decay constants 
for commonly encountered radioactive isotopes:

{
<table><tr><th>**Isotope**</th><th>**Half-Life**</th><th>**Decay Constant $k$**</th><th>**Model**</th></tr><tr><td>Technetium-99m</td><td>6.01 hours</td><td>0.1153/hr</td><td>$A = A_0 e^{-0.1153t}$</td></tr><tr><td>Iodine-131</td><td>8.02 days</td><td>0.0864/day</td><td>$A = A_0 e^{-0.0864t}$</td></tr><tr><td>Phosphorus-32</td><td>14.3 days</td><td>0.0485/day</td><td>$A = A_0 e^{-0.0485t}$</td></tr><tr><td>Strontium-90</td><td>28.8 years</td><td>0.0241/yr</td><td>$A = A_0 e^{-0.0241t}$</td></tr><tr><td>Cesium-137</td><td>30.2 years</td><td>0.0230/yr</td><td>$A = A_0 e^{-0.0230t}$</td></tr><tr><td>Carbon-14</td><td>5,730 years</td><td>$1.21 \times 10^{-4}$/yr</td><td>$A = A_0 e^{-0.000121t}$</td></tr><tr><td>Plutonium-239</td><td>24,100 years</td><td>$2.88 \times 10^{-5}$/yr</td><td>$A = A_0 e^{-0.0000288t}$</td></tr><tr><td>Uranium-238</td><td>4.47 billion years</td><td>$1.55 \times 10^{-10}$/yr</td><td>—</td></tr></table>
}
**Note:** $k = \ln(2)/h \approx 0.693/h$. Units of $k$ match units of half-life.
